The Prague Stock Exchange finished with fewer points at the end of the day
After the morning's rapid fall, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
The transactions in ČEZ shares reached approximately half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the start of Tuesday's trading, reacted immediately to the fall on Monday when it fell to about 6%.
This time the drop is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
This is also the market reaction to the result of the vote in the American House of Representatives which refused to support the financial sector secretary's stabilization plan.
Shares fall in Asia
The Asian stock market experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although the index eventually eased some of its losses.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index throughout its financial day marked almost four percent, although it later eased its losses by reducing the decline by practically 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index that tracks the movements of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, the losses fell to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange according to the Index Secretary fell to 3.6 percent.
"The planned bailout actions in the US are uncertain and this is influencing the financial markets around the world", said Hong Kong Monetary Office Chief Joseph Yam.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, i.e. without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong's interest rates are at the same level as those in the United States.
US lawmakers should reconvene as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that the falls will be felt in other countries.
Bloodbath of American stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected a plan to help the financial system that would require $700 billion (about $12 billion).
The lawmakers, in that way, ignored President George Bush's invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would solve the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, American stocks experienced a bloody dip and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in over 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell to nearly seven percent, a drop in volume similar to the last recorded in 1987.
The index dropped before it was announced but as soon as it was shown that the assembly's proposal was not going forward, the index began to fall freely.
Congress retreats: US government can inject 700 billion dollars into the bank
The highest representatives of Congress and the government, President George W. Bush, agreed on a broad-based agreement to provide financial assistance to the American financial system.
The vote will take place early next week.
US lawmakers caused a rift in talks over the approval of the bailout plan in the form of a $700 billion (about 12 trillion kronor) bailout for the American financial system.
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must refine some details of the contract before they can make public the final form of the law and have it voted.
The plan to help the financial system will be discussed Monday in the House of Representatives.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Financial Services and Banking Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to some sources, the vote on the plan could be held in the Senate no earlier than Wednesday.
According to economists, the arrival of the ratification of the bailout plan should represent the announcement of a first psychologically significant factor for the revitalization of the financial market.
But then there will be 'disillusionment' thanks to the complex mechanisms which will also be achieved in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great strides.
We resolve our divergent views on how the package of measures for market stabilization should be", said Democratic Nancy Pelosi to Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could still take place on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met Sunday night with the Minister of Finance, Henry Paulson, to give a definitive shape to the government fund.
It should buy from financial corporations the unsold mortgage assets which lead to heavy losses for financial corporations and threaten the stability of the whole system.
"We are about to conclude the agreement on the plan, which will work and must also be effective in the market.
It is still necessary to continue with the sanitation plan, but I think we are already on it", said Paulson.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is having a clear impact on the rapidly declining stock market.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are doing everything they can to get Congress to finally pass a deal this Sunday.
They want to reassure investors' business in the Asian financial market, which is in the first time zone and where Congress could influence Monday's trade.
However, at the moment it is not clear for sure when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote and even if they will not stall at the last moment with some problem.
The lawmakers believe it will be approved in the next few days.
The law, however, will undergo a series of changes.
The total amount intended to help the system should be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion must be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush requested.
However, Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it has the impression that the program is not fulfilling its function, which would be another $100 billion and, later, the last $350 billion.
Bush appreciated the progress of the meetings
On the other hand, the president can veto this decision but Congress can override his veto by a majority vote.
Despite these changes, the basic idea of the program was to earn financial resources to buy back bad mortgage bonds whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to finish paying their mortgages.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be ready to vote on the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday", Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
President Bush is also satisfied with the progress of the meetings.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, announced that Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and appreciated "the commitment on both sides to stabilize our financial market and protect our economy".
Limitation of the armored contract
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, said lawmakers decided on the responsibility of the money program for protecting taxpayers' taxes from their losses, a relief closure of the scheduled finance plan.
The new law should also limit so-called shielded contracts for directors of the participating companies in the programme, and create a committee that will have control of the Fund.
This one should be run by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on it, and we have made great progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans", Paulson said.
The plan also assists homeowners who have problems with their payments.
The government would have to agree to new mortgage payments to lower the monthly payment burden on borrowers and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: psychological help
The proposed plan is, according to the chief economist of Patria Finance, David Marek, a good idea that will be implemented but quite difficult.
"And that is why it is not known with what mechanism and at what price the problem assets will be purchased.
This will be decisive for the distribution of losses between the financial sector and the government", Marek said this week, for the server iHNed.cz.
Whether the plan is approved now or early next week is not, according to Marek, that relevant.
"Much more important is that, this week, the congressmen agree on their support and give their approval as soon as possible.
This important and psychological agreement to reach that approval is, at this moment, the most important thing", Marek insisted.
Armed hand-to-hand combat: the MP3 player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
Which makes it seem clear that it's better to just buy the phone.
Yet there are sufficient reasons for man to acquire only the reproducer.
The choice depends almost entirely on the way it is used and the demands of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for me to acquire the most modern turntable to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc album.
Moreover, such musical products as LP records are no longer available, and as far as their quality is concerned there is no objective reason to continue buying them.
If you have art rock, jazz, or blues vinyl records on your shelves, you are probably dreaming, at least, of this type of turntable.
This is the same with music that's on the way, that is, compressed music, simplified music -- MP3 music.
And here there are price and quality categories.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try the merchandise helmets of twenty crowns.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also decides the battery life
Some of the best players do a lot more than just play music and even that which even most mobile phones don't.
No other device today is as universal as the telephone.
In contrast to the most basic functions like calling, sending messages, it can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera and even navigate.
And when we consider the smartphone and the PDAs you're going to have in your pocket a little computer too.
This is a small miracle since no refrigerator can make a grill and no television can photograph.
The universality of mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your phone, the earlier the indicator on the screen will light up, asking to be recharged.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy drains.
Few mobile phones can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest) are clearly more efficient.
So keep in mind that cheap phones won't play for more than two hours.
If in addition to this, on top of that, they constantly call for a charger for work - this is also true for the most expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player this problem will not have, because even the worst can withstand at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small proportion of the devices have the universal USB connector and not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course it is possible to record music directly to the memory card but only some unreduced playback units can be connected to the small memory cards used in mobile phones.
In the case of players, with one exception (iPod), no special software is required.
Just fill the device with music through the computer's USB.
Most mobile phones and players create their own order in the music library according to the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to the user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (river, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
When choosing a particular device, consider the battery's strength, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of handling.
If you listen to music in the background and listen to it only once a day, like on the tram, then you can use any mobile phone that plays it.
Which practically gets any real mobile.
You should not even care about the format in which the mobile phone or the player plays the music.
MP3 is played by everyone, and practically all the music you get will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and, with the exception of it, the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
The fewest include the AAC format (the format used by Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough to visit the relevant websites of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album via the mobile internet.
This service alone could be a strong argument for purchasing a mobile for music.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is poor and most of them are limited to the topics of short-lived radio success.
Prices aren't the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that this very way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry a mobile phone with them.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you'll find your phone in your pocket, while your MP3 player will be left at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or, at least, handsfree ones.
If not, you can use an integrated player that virtually every mobile has, even if it's at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the music phones will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can already buy a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the absence of a classic headphone ticket.
The best, even in terms of the technical part, such as phones equipped with a 3.5 mm input for classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of players is nothing but their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are actually handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, their handling similar to the previous ordinary cassettes or also to the turntables is evident.
It's not a threat in the sense that we accidentally connect to the internet with our mobile and, consequently, a huge data download bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for changing the memory card (M2 type, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a proper card it will reach two thousand crowns.
Be careful, though.
Basic models are usually equipped with only a 2 GB card of maximum capacity.
Only the most expensive ones have 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile and you want to buy a cheap MP3 player, check out Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
According to the capacity (maximum 2 GB), no more than 1.100 crowns need to be spent.
If you are considered among the most demanding music lovers, you can use the most specialized mobile walk-man (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of a single player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose walkman line phones have almost identical use as a standalone MP3 player.
The same service and the same price category, over four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery (usually 15 hours, with a maximum output of up to 35 hours), the brand mentioned above brings them MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we are still missing something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
He'll probably be here any minute.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) also confirmed the rest, warning that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the latest steps by the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition that really wants to fight.
This is probably paradoxical to us, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The President of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no longer any place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a traditional operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find any frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market led to a significant price decline, to which the traditional operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, we need not look too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain over 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
Mobilking is also the parent company of Penta, which also owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is that they can concentrate on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order to operate effectively, they only need to have far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They do not entail relatively large expenditure on network construction, operation and maintenance.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually characterised by low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages which, however, are often countered by the offer of more tight services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half the price of the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a trivial target group can also be a good hit.
This operator is specifically targeting the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator he likes and can trust", says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which runs this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as that of Poland could catch on in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts this: 'The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated".
In the Czech Republic, there are no chances, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is any virtual operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic. It does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region", said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, in a telephone conversation for mobil.cz.
He indirectly stated that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try their best to prevent any potential competition from arising.
Interest in launching a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group, which would like to take a step further to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We are very interested in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile telephone services.
And the sooner the better.
We have met with all Czech mobile operators on this occasion.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings", said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they're flashing better times.
It seems that, from unofficial information, the first official operator should arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now, his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
'At the moment we believe that the situation is right for a virtual operator to appear on the Czech market.
The Czech market is a very specific market compared to others.
So far no one has approached us with any complex and serious project in this field", said Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
Other operators are mentioned in the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with the O2 opinion, adds: 'To date we have not registered any viable commercial project that can be further developed with bilateral benefits.'
He adds: "On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should have on the table some concrete contract that could be studied in such a short time horizon".
Vodafone is focusing instead on meeting the requirements of a 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepický adds: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this is in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the biggest contribution from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is to establish a partner with whom to share a network for fast mobile internet.
Responsible offices - with the nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, which would lead to lower prices and, with them, lower profits.
So why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull on the same string, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the ČTÚ was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is borne out by the public information available on the ČTÚ website.
But now U:fon is the argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: 'In addition, the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was recently opened up to a fourth operator.
As regards the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail high requirements for him and, above all, for his services.'
This is why this access to mobile operators is extremely discouraging because of the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the CTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries.
This is purely the responsibility of the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tendering (ÚOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this problem.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the lease of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator is concluded.
No agreement has been concluded to date as the offer of potential interested parties was not sufficiently interesting for traditional operators", added Kristián Chalupa, from the Department of Foreign Affairs at the ÚOHS.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices which are supposed to represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from this they must see that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign countries where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile phone services".
Obviously, pressure on the proper functioning of the market and price reduction are not in the interest of the ÚOHS.
What is really dramatically shocking about this whole case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it is really a coincidence, it comes up by itself.
It is the same as the price of petrol at petrol stations, for it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
'The Office has not found any signs of unfair competition in this respect and therefore has no grounds for intervening in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore they do not have a corresponding increase in responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecommunications regulators", added Chalupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of conflict.
There is of course an analysis of relevant markets by the ČTÚ which shows that telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of commercial tendering.
In this type of market, naturally, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for a virtual operator to emerge, agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
It must therefore necessarily be dominant in a particular segment.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for ÚOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators are promoted in strikingly similar ways.
The current complaints from interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they encounter many similar impediments.
The charge of responsibility on the ČTÚ is a common trick in the telecommunications field from which the ÚOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We've met him before in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the Telecommunications Act to extend the competence of the ČTÚ in the field of commercial tenders was recently tabled, but it was not implemented, despite the promises of a number of experts that the situation would improve.
The representatives of the OHIM should know this, but their interests are clearly elsewhere.
Everything's fine when no one's looking
At the same time, a kind of pseudo-virtual operator is still operating unnoticed, and there are already a few of them in the Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that set their own prices for mobile telephony services, but only a part of them are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally only a select few get the price list from these companies.
The magic is that the company, in relation to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer, you will receive special prices and other offers later.
The problem is that the commercial conditions at all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases like the one you mention were discovered, it could be a breach of the terms of the contract which could result in the end of the partnership with the company", Martina Kemrová said.
But it is quite unlikely that such activity by mobile phone operators would not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, it may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
They make a considerable profit from their activities and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the potential problems: "the law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name and therefore cannot have it at their disposal as a normal customer of the carriers".
This is precisely what should seem to the CTU minimally strange.
A new question for the OHIM is also added.
If mobile phone operators are blindfolded in this kind of procedure, why block the virtual operator's entry?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has sufficient competence to detect such activities and if it does not wish to do so it should not be satisfied with the operators' explanations that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When we stop being the most expensive
As already stated in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market led to a significant drop in the prices of the services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where the virtual operator emerged, the traditional operators more or less tried to protect themselves from this breakthrough.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have intervened and in none of the cases have they defended the operators but their customers.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual operator and with it, others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority is treating this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
We cannot but be impressed by our experience that confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If one of the operators allows in a virtual mobile operator it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four performances of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new official recording of the anthem Where is my home on the occasion of the official Czech celebrations.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two solo versions, one with male and one female vocals, one with choir and one instrumental.
The singing is handled by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national anthem to be one of the most beautiful.
Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose for the Solos singers with representatively younger voices who are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried with both and then, also, with the Choir to fixate on the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it had consonance", he said.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, My Home was first played in 1834 on the boards of the State Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with music by František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it their own.
The first verse of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 naturally became part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
