Prague MHD takes us Wednesday for the first time with the chip
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers enter the subway, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can be purchased at this moment by almost 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously charge it to their chip card at the information centres and stations of the transport company at the Metro stations, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The bonds can be purchased from yesterday on the internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by over four hundred people.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of commerce may start to forget about the ticket booths at subway stations, where they had to regularly queue up to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is a window with prepared staff available to passengers to help interested parties with the purchase via the internet and also with the recharge of the voucher purchased on their card", said the project's spokesman, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic voucher on the Opencard at the vending machines located in some lobbies of the metro.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, reminiscent of a ticket machine, and travellers have probably already noticed them at the metro stations of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are five in the city now but by the end of the year there should be eighty", Opatrný added.
The bond is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid voucher will be loaded onto it alone.
Electronic bonds are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
That is to say, in the ring trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the localities of central Bohemia.
"In the trains assigned to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reading card that will help to confirm the validity of the time and the zone of the bonus", explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that establishes the hours of collective transport of Prague.
The round-trip buses have their reading cards mounted on the driver's cab.
When entering, the driver must not only be shown the card but must also be accompanied by the Opencard at the designated place on the side of the Box.
The driver then controls the validity of the voucher.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than requesting this information from the driver", Drápal added.
Passengers who do not travel on the round-trip buses and do not remember when the voucher expires may go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown the information about the validity of your document.
Southeasterners wanted to be part of the United States in a referendum.
The German Sudets asked in 1945 that Fumaba be part of the United States.
This is what is extracted from the letter which is kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With this desire, presumably, some groups of Germans from the Sudetes addressed the president of the United States in 1945.
It is the result of letters kept in a private archive and now kept in the collection of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Český Krumlov request in a letter to the American president that he not allow the return of the "Sumava land" - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Pact - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we really want your word that American units are coming to German lands not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators", the letter reads, signed by a "people who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts".
Since the union of Czechoslovakia with the southeastern Germans presumably implies - according to them the Czech national character - a hope only in brutality, recklessness, misunderstanding, pressure and slavery, the authors beg in the letter the American president to assume for now and forever Šumava under a protectorate.
"We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million inhabitants we are handed over to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way collaborates with the victory of the allies", the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is presumably fear of reprisals from the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States is presumably in doubt about this idea of the Šumav Germans, it would be enough to organize a referendum in the Šumav lands on whether its inhabitants want to be part of the United States or live under its patronage.
Although the letter's text, with our current knowledge of postwar history, may sound a bit childish, some experts say it paints a vivid picture of the expectations of the Germans of the southeast at the time.
Although the Czech Germans must have had a slight intuition that it was going to be about their expulsion from the republic, only a few admitted this possibility.
Some hoped that the United States and Britain would negotiate for the Sudetenland some clear form of autonomy.
Others thought they would stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed even by the Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
This one was in the war, as a Budějovice German, enlisted in the Baltic navy.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and placed in the Holstein prison camp, dozens of Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They thought that when they came home, the Czech would be useful", said Chalupa.
None of the German prisoners who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, he said, counted on the Benes Decrees to keep them away from the Republic.
