Eatonville, the first fully incorporated black-inhabited city in the country and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 men of color, 300 good swimmers, many guayabas, two schools and not a jail".
It's a place of pilgrimage now.
