"It has to be right".
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is at the same time a historic model of the affirmation of blacks and a community of nearly 2,400 people living below a poverty level twice the national average.
It's a literary center, but also a restored example of the rural black southern culture - sometimes disregarded, sometimes praised - that was born out of slavery in America.
No wonder, if those who reside here are both proud and reserved.
And the concern for Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as no one here calls her Mrs Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her profound dialect books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through central Florida often forgotten inward about black history and human drama.
With a face of cement in both life and literature, Mrs. Hurston took her readers to the store owned by the first mayor of Eatonville, Joe Clarke, and then into more private areas.
"Off the road on the left", he wrote, "is the modern brown public school with its white finishes, its well-kept gardens and playgrounds, cared for by Howard Miller, as he can scarcely read and write".
She also mentions the widow Dash's new husband and writes that Glenn Lee "sells all kinds of drinks and anything goes with transient rooms".
So in just a few hundred words Mrs Hurston relates Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriages and sex.
Obviously, this Fodor didn't.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
"Zora described it as it was", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls that Mrs. Hurston immortalized by quoting men who were singing colourless songs about her beauty.
