But, she adds, swinging in her chair in a backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Mrs. Hurston was likely baptized, "she never stayed too long".
When Mrs Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were no longer in print.
Like most of the world, Eatonville also seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only woman of color at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had been living.
