She was a freestyle dancer and specialist in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, a pioneer of women's liberation, like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian and advocated for the abolition of the corset which prevented women's free movement.
The life of this woman, who marked a dance and aesthetic revolution in Europe between the wars, fascinated Isabel Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me and I thought it was amazing".
According to the dancer, "we do not intend to tell her life but to collect her spirit.
The titles of your dances have suggested flamenco sticks.
So, "the butterfly dance" suggested to me a guajira, or "the snake dance" a tango.
Their dance was sensual and I have been told that my dance is also within this aesthetic", he says.
The montage has two exceptional collaborations: that of Miguel Poveda who will sing again to Isabel in one of his shows, just as he did in that of "The open door"; and with the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to collaborate with whoever was his student.
"Matilde plays the elder Tortola, the character of maturity.
I am happy that she has agreed to act in my play and I am very honored for that".
The installation also features the musical composition and guitars of Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, the canto of Miguel Ortega, the Pulga and Moi de Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa El Viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfra Juárez, "who plays the role of the eternal companion of this type of artists who were divas in all their extension, and who are always in love with them".
The work also tells in some way the life of this woman who developed in places so far away, especially for the time, such as India, the United States, or Russia, in addition to all over Europe, since she usually resided in London.
"I wanted to remember her because I think she is one of those women who have a huge influence in a certain time and now nobody knows and much less values her work", says Bayón.
