Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean these kids who wake up very smart telling us something that happened the day before, but kids who talk while they're asleep.
The first time it happens, you might get a little scared, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a benign sleep disorder called somnolence.
It's quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one person has heard that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its occurrence.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (sleeping) or sleepwalking, but this need not be the case.
As we have already mentioned, they can also be associated with periods of very high fever, stress or overexcitation.
It's a little studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a calm tone, loose words, a murmur, or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches, etc.).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to see if there is any issue that is generating much anxiety and giving rise to it in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before bed.
So seek quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that are frightening or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them to acquire a measure of inner calm.
This will help the child to sleep more peacefully.
Once the sleepwalking occurs try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
Helpful Tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's unconscious, and you'll break his sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's sleeping and therefore resting.
Remember, if he is very distressed for several episodes, you might want to consult or find out what is causing the child so much anxiety.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the norm), do not be tempted to ask him questions to get information.
