The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most efficient blood suppliers in the world.
And most of all, it regained the public's trust that had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In the face of this tragedy and public discontent, the government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his report, certain provinces then set up a committee whose goal was to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its operations, almost 38 percent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec", recalls Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After making many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and much work over the years that followed, we have regained the public's trust", he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had subsequently trusted Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, reminds us that "trust is extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we saw the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, in Europe, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
So we have taken one of the main recommendations from the Krever and Gélineau reports, which is that when we do not know and when a serious disease may result from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain which inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we refused blood from people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But some years ago it was proved beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense".
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that detect the presence of the virus directly in the blood of donors and not antibodies to the virus, which were the basis for the tests used until now.
Nucleic acid tests shortened the time between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
We're significantly reducing the risk that certain donors are unknowingly infected and unable to be detected.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from blood transfusions.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before anyone is infected with HIV.
So since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be over 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today one can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain health without worries", says the head of Héma-Québec's management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island. Like the West Nile virus, it is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant", continues Dr Décary before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
"Needs increase as the population ages.
Since the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the blood donor network, which on average comprises only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate blood.
All persons in good health, aged 18 and over who meet the eligibility criteria may nevertheless donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Hardships are very rare.
But members of this donor network need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but more importantly to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Since life is so unbridled today, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating your blood", laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases like leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, the placement in the bank of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample and it is expected to take more than a thousand of these per year.
We should start proposing it for grafts early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this", since Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
