Wall Street bailout - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republican and Democratic, finally reached agreement yesterday on the most important economic bailout plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to stem the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months still needs to be confirmed by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular for better control by the elected representatives of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of foreclosed houses and non-payment, and a tax on the salaries paid to the managers of the firms receiving aid.
The US Treasury Secretary, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We are making great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets", said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to cover up the economy and ordinary Americans in the current crisis on Wall Street", the Democrat explained.
"It's the bottom line: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense", Republican Judd Gregg declared.
The negotiations had been concluded very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect of a new failure on the investor mood.
The last time they had set was for the markets to open this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have joined the negotiations late, were rather in favour of the agreement, without forgetting to express their dissatisfaction at having to go to this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly the one that would allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one about the salary of the heads of the surviving companies by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, we should not be congratulated.
But these measures are necessary", he said on American television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, asked on another network if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied that "I'd like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it".
"The important points I read [shows] that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we can move forward.
He said the option of doing nothing is not acceptable".
The 700 billion plan is to buy with taxpayers' money the dubious debts, risky assets and untradable assets of American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages before spreading to other more common forms of credit securities (CCBS) and causing a liquidity freeze and a run-down of banks and financial institutions.
It's a group of Republican elected officials who had the first draft of the agreement changed last week.
We think we've come out of the stalemate since the Democrats agreed that certain "toxic" assets of struggling companies should only be insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to settle the rough patches for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that if the government had to take losses for five years with this program, it could impose new fees that would purportedly help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion, to which 100 billion may be added if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion would have to be confirmed by another vote by Congress.
In return for his help, Washington will get stakes in the rescued companies that will pay dividends on profits and that it can sell back when the storm is over.
The Federal Government will have the possibility to delay foreclosure proceedings concerning housing obtained with real estate loans under this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and on cash compensation paid to the managers of companies affected by the crisis.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the House of Representatives vote today and to the Senate next Wednesday.
Despite all his efforts, he's still not sure that his plan will be approved.
Some people continued to protest yesterday against this bill, both from the Republicans and Democrats.
Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents that "with all the evidence, Washington doesn't want to understand".
"We have a very serious financial problem.
There are solutions.
But not the one that involves taking advantage of the taxpayers".
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, who is a small-group cheerleader in Congress, presents the issues in a different way, but he comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us to say: we ask the Congress not to rush and to examine carefully the path to take", he declared yesterday.
At this very moment, in Europe, we had again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an urgent meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion dollars).
