What did they produce at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. bill factory?
Very soon, on October 8, the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant damage, in a business manner, continuously and in an organized manner in addition to other crimes, including forgery of documents.
According to the prosecutor, they used for their own purposes the funds obtained in the public tenders, justifying the fulfillment of the tasks with false invoices.
The public and municipal funds - totalling some HUF 65 million - were partly in the treasury of the Fiatal Baloldal organisation and partly in the pocket of private individuals.
The method, which was also disclosed by the investigators, was to justify the collection of the funds obtained in the public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the various associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the bills were false.
To do this, they obtained the talonaries from the market in Józsefváros District and the circular seals were manufactured in the city of Kiskunhalas.
The question of which company was to issue the counterfeit invoice was decided, among others, during the tour of the Upper Balaton Region, where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for a bill for his consumption and these served as a model for making the bills he presented among others in the contests of the Ministry of Juvenile and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor, as well as in the City Hall of the Capital.
These bills were signed mostly by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information rather wrote the reports necessary to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this food centre provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the centre manager - so many people cannot fit in at the same time.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
A hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and no more than ten people could stay there in one night, yet the bill was for one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of fantastic invoices also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft. gastronomic center because in the bookkeeping of the same - according to the information given to the Fiscal - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecutor's office and shown the invoices, he already knew that they were fake documents.
"The stamp had our company name and NIF in the wrong place".
He added: besides the formal problems, he did not agree that according to the bill, one hundred people were accommodated, since they have only eleven rooms in which not so many people can fit.
Also, the bill included meals, while the restaurant has been out of business for a while.
The enthusiastic invoice makers were also not informed that the travel agency chosen in Budapest exclusively organises trips abroad, so that in the cash invoice they foolishly indicated as a service a trip within Hungary, which was not in line with the agency's invoice issuing practice either.
In addition - as was found during the investigation - they included VAT in the document as well, even though travel outside the territory of the European Union was exempt from tax.
The VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért foundation, since the services of that company are not charged 25 but only 15 per cent VAT, and the hotel employees only handed out machine-made invoices, although the invoice was handwritten.
In addition, the "shippers" made other mistakes as well, such as in the case of a company in which they put in the invoice as an activity carried out the road transport to which - it was known during the investigations of the prosecutor's office - does not carry out the company founded as investment consultant.
Also due to formal differences - inadequate form of the invoice, false stamp - it was found that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont are false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued those invoices.
The counterfeiters also paid attention to the fact that when the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in the process of liquidation, so the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
They sent out the bills consciously
Another group of counterfeiters are those who were aware that they should issue fake invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about HUF four million in the name of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of Collab Kft. - according to the prosecution - was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
Similarly, Biogate Kft., currently in liquidation, cooperated with Zuschlag and its accomplices, which in 2003 supplied invoices worth approximately HUF 5 million to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, without any real economic activity behind them.
There was no capital movement either, because afterwards they cancelled the bills prepared but forgot to include this entity in their documents.
The next group of counterfeiters include those who have some connection to the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the plaintiff of the Ukrainian manager of the fictitious Budapest-based Delta Trio SL, which dealt in the sale of fuel and vehicles.
This company issued numerous invoices for the sale of computer media worth approximately HUF 18 million in October, November and December 2005.
According to the investigation data, these invoices were purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which has been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian, to whom Ivan Kubatov should have also sent the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices on behalf of the company for the Atlasz, for the Hoppá and for the Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány collecting the amount himself.
Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies actually worked because - according to the defendant - they did not get work.
But he took advantage of these companies, for at the request of his accomplice, lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the company's registration documents, they issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the organizations linked to Zuschlag: to the Atlasz and to the Y-Generáció.
Kubatov on behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trio, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade issued a total of 15 invoices to different entities for a value of HUF 14,2 million.
The prosecution considered that Kubatov received VAT and 10% of the invoice amount.
That man even took advantage of the Szi-Beri joint-stock company to issue fictitious bills used in Biztos Pont's contest.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted a competition in January 2006 to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility entity of the Socialist Party.
The tender received 500 thousand HUF respectively, but did not use the money for the tender objectives.
To avoid this being discovered, they presented the TMA with five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft.
These were the invoices found during the registration of the office that Árpád Kemecsei had at the headquarters of the Ministry of Education.
Some of the defendants will probably relate at the trial - as they did at the Prosecutor's Office - the course of the counterfeiting of the invoices.
The most interesting thing may be the confession of the main accused János Zuschlag himself, if he decides to dismantle everything.
Well, his confessions so far have not been very detailed and although he repeatedly promised to talk about everything, he hasn't done so until now.
The question is: what is his interest in doing so? For perhaps in return for the return of most of the money - 50 million HUF - the socialists have reached an agreement with him for Zusi to assume all the responsibilities.
Who, on the other hand, for these days even could be offended, since to alleviate his prison conditions he requested house arrest, but was repeatedly denied.
While the numerous perpetrators of far superior economic crimes, who never returned the money, roam freely or at least can wait in their own homes for sentencing, he has no chance of that.
The psychology of overlapping: Why do we spend more money?
Participants in auctions are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological-economic basis for this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study in the journal Science, people don't want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological pattern of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in an auction, and the active areas of the participants' brains were examined by means of the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games, participants could win money, but during auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called the stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-reward" mechanism.
So, according to scientists, the increase in gambling is explained as a prevention to avoid provoking an intense stratum reaction.
To support their theory, the economists in the scientific group also carried out a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and their members bet.
Another group was also promised an additional $15 prize if they won.
Instead, the third group received exactly 15 dollars before the auction, but if they lost the auction, the group members lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that one group highlighted success and the other group highlighted failure.
However, testing the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the "failure" group were willing to gamble even more than members of the control group and the "win" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
The Commission has not yet decided on the future of the Community.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation", said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should you see a doctor?
Worldwide some 500 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are receiving treatment because many of the sick do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for various liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause are very different.
Hepatitis viruses dependent on the pathogen are spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. contaminated water or food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal fluid, saliva).
Travellers are advised to be vaccinated against A and B viruses, as there are no vaccines against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating the infected food, manifesting as general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After that jaundice appears on the skin and white of the eyes, the feces become clear, the urine dark and the healing can last up to two - three weeks.
Each year a million people die worldwide from cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected persons receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know they are sick because this pathogen gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms do not appear until 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early detection, systematic medical monitoring, is very important.
The disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and those who have tattoos.
There are now some 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
Since this disease can be detected by routine laboratory testing as well, it is worth consulting your family doctor if you experience any unknown symptoms.
The disease has a cure if discovered early, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so that the contagion can be suppressed and cancer prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients.
It aims to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and to the importance of early detection.
Does it hurt less for those who believe in God?
According to a recent study, religious faith has a calming effect that even eased the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment: They analyzed how religious belief influences human pain, reports Britain's Telegraph newspaper.
In this unique experiment, they electrocuted 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was verified that the Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in a series of research projects involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from the University's various departments.
The analysis was done in the following way: A sparkling instrument was attached to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants to look at two paintings - the 17th-century Virgin Mary by Sassoferrato and the 15th-century Lady of the Armino by Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers hoped that the Virgin Mary spectacle would evoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a calming effect.
Patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during that time while observing either the religious-themed painting or the other.
Catholics said that looking at the Virgin Mary made them feel "secure" as "protected" persons, "soothed and peace reigned in their hearts".
When they looked at the religious painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's painting.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image that's so shocking, you can get a similar effect on atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find a portrait of a person for whom they feel very positive, like a mother or a father", the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases does change our personality", Wright added.
After these formidable results, there is only one question left: What effect would it have on pain regulation if the faithful were shown the Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of his stature?
Would a high-quality vision of the Virgin Mary produce even better results?
You are what you say about yourself
On its tenth birthday, Google can claim: it can be found in people's pockets as well as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which doctors they visit and what interests them.
But according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's executives, this is still not enough.
On the other hand, skeptics who draw a parallel with the Orwellian vision do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main goal is to collect as much personal data as possible about its users, and this is necessary to fulfill the original goals of Google's founders: "We bring together all the information in the world in one system!"
According to the head of Google, the company even after ten years of work that revolutionized the world is still in the initial phase of the endeavor to be able to process all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years' time, Schmidt replied: I wish Google could answer questions like "What will I do tomorrow?" or "What would be the best job for me?" - but software cannot answer seemingly simple questions as long as there is not enough information from users.
Not all Internet users are aware that during their browsing on the Web, the keywords they searched for, the IP addresses and the pages they went to at the end of the search are stored accurately.
For example, Personalized Search, which debuted two years ago, allows users to store their own browsing history, they can consult what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - on this same logic will be based the Recommendations, in which the system will offer us products and services based on the preferences previously defined and stored.
What will happen if they use my data against me, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who are concerned about seeing Google's information monopoly.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, yearning for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is a confirmed fact that not only do they retain, but in justifiable cases they also transfer to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing to protect the personal rights of internet users.
Perhaps the most debated example of recent times was the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, when Google gave the Brazilian government information from its Web page, called Orkut, to identify pedophiles.
However, Internet users concerned about human rights were relieved in May when the company, along with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully proved before the court that it was right in its dispute with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google cannot be forced, by any of the constitution's points, to provide any kind of information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to obtain, under the pretext of strengthening the child protection law passed years ago, some 50,000 web addresses and some 1,000 search phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor complete lists of web pages and keywords for the last two months.)
This is a rather contradictory view of Google: it is criticized by those who are afraid to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy, their private life is damaged by starting to use Google services, and they rebel against it as against multinational companies with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, the North American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, Internet users and users from other countries, see in them the next generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not so their rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as the conqueror of the World, however much both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free software package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks see precisely the very problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet that was produced by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, about leaving intentional footprints behind us and leveraging the available communication channels, and while the measurements of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous social pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them to other services, such as Twitter or last.fm which offers a list of his music habits, after which he can include them in a tracking system such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, he can also have a blog, where the most recent photo galleries that are stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
We can know numerous cases from which it follows that for example the girlfriend, by seeing the flow of photographs of the next morning of common friends, finds out who her fraudulent boyfriend spent the night with or they can fire the employee of a company because he writes his honest opinion on his blog about the management of the company: one thing is certain, the definition of privacy was completely re-evaluated.
A person's online life is what they show themselves - this is the definition behind the behavior of today's youth.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least wants to dodge Google's monopoly, can do it (starting with the Scroogle, for example, which uses Google's search engine, but leaves no trace).
There are many people who don't want to register on the collective pages to avoid being found, but you can replace Google's "online" applications, from text-writing software to image and news-reading applications with alternative versions that don't connect to giant servers or prepare the most perfect profile possible about us.
Public opinion is almost openly waiting for the day when Google shows its true face.
