The intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best method for developing technologies to avoid collisions if not by imitating obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the one about the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C type robotic steering system for cars that mimics nature, giving it the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, RP and development and research technology director at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the compound eyes of bumblebees, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eyes, the engineers used the laser-beam length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within 2 metres, at a 180-degree angle, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle's microprocessor which is immediately transformed into a collision avoidance maneuver.
In a fraction of a second, the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle's robot, imitating the movements of the bumblebees, changes direction by turning the wheels as needed.
Unlike any system currently in existence, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"Without this, the vehicle robot would not be able to react quickly enough to dodge obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety capsule, in a layer within which all kinds of collisions are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process should reflect what one bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels
So instead of the infinite possibilities for the bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used the rotary motion and acceleration plus braking as a possibility for the car's robot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries which are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, what is important is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the capacity to process data, much less the storage capacity.
This apparatus should only process a few input signals per second and react accordingly.
There is no need to store this data or react with instinctive logic based on the data from the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
You don't need gigabytes of memory, you don't need megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge the obstacles, which Nissan estimates will be incorporated into series-produced models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, dodging obstacles in his way.
