The written version of the law has been prepared for the $700 billion financial rescue package that will be implemented in several phases to buy bad loans from banks.
Half the money will be spent in the first phase.
According to Eastern time during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion financial rescue package after several days of discussion, Reuters reported.
We have made important progress, said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic president of the US Congress, saying that all that remains is to formalize the agreement in a document.
The commitment made on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise, said: "This program will work and be efficient but other measures are needed". According to Pelosi, it's not about saving Wall Street, but turning the wheel of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, i.e. before 8 p.m. on Sunday, Washington time (i.e. before 2 a.m. on Monday, Central European time), without causing a dramatic jump in the stock markets.
The bill called the 2008 Economic Stabilization Emergency Act will be voted on Monday first by the U.S. Congress and then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news of the deal.
We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
The program is different from the Bush administration's original proposal to spend all 700 billion dollars to buy bad credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion will be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of which the Treasury will buy bad credit-fund securities, and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This programme will be controlled by a special body, in which the chairman of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion will be spent after a new decision by Congress.
Under the law the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and securities, credit fund securities, plus other "poisonous" loans as well.
The purchase can be done by auction or directly - informed competent persons of the ministry.
The law allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme where the financial portfolio guarantees the items of concern, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said: the law thus ensures the necessary financial means, which can reach up to 700 billion dollars to meet the urgent needs of the North American financial system, be it the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We are doing everything necessary to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed - he added.
Instead, the heads of the banks who are in trouble and waiting for state help will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensation, which the American slang simply calls gold parachutes.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and the limitations depend on the form of aid from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on gold parachutes, unless the failed bank boss retires.
By buying bad credit directly, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the compensation of the bosses is not overstated.
In addition, the existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations are only for new contracts to stimulate participation in the programme.
This is the first time in American history that a legal limitation on the income of general managers will be in effect - said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional committee responsible for financial services.
The State will also be entitled to acquire shares of the banks participating in the programme, thus reducing the risk for taxpayers, who will ultimately be able to profit from the transaction once the economy and the bank recover.
According to the bill, in the next five years, the president must present to Congress a proposal on how to pay back taxpayers for financial sector losses.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed reservations about the project.
This is not what the American citizens have entrusted us with, that is, they are not protecting taxpayer dollars - declared Republican Congressman Darrell Issa of California.
His Ohio Democrat colleague, Mary Kaptur, said the measures were urged by the same people responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007's prices, the Central Statistics Office (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices increased by 1,1% compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3,9% compared to the previous year.
As a result of the changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0,7% compared to the previous month and by 3,2% compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only marginally, by 0.1%.
Domestic selling prices in the manufacturing sector increased slightly, by 0.1% compared with July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2,8%) due primarily to the increase of 4,6% in bags and belts and the increase of 2,5% in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials production branch (1.6%).
Price declines were recorded in the petrochemical sector (1.4%), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9%) and, to a lesser extent, in the wood processing sector (0.1%).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing remained unchanged.
In the rest of the processing industry, prices increased by between 0.2 and 0.9%.
The supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which are important in domestic trade, increased by 0.3% in August, primarily as a result of the increase in official prices from 1 July.
In a comparison over a 12-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4%).
The metalworking sector saw an increase of 13.2%, while the food, beverage and tobacco industry, which was a major player, saw an increase of 11%.
Prices fell in the textile industry (2.5%) and in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3%).
In the other processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6% and 9.1%.
Over the past year, prices in the processing industry have risen by 10.2 per cent globally.
Prices for electricity, gas, heat and water supplies were 18.7 percent higher than the previous year.
In August, the largest monthly price increase (0.7%) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sector, prices rose by 0.3%, in the energy sector and in the intermediate sectors, prices were unchanged compared with the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest price increases were recorded in the energy sector and intermediate industry (16.8%) compared to the same month of the previous year.
In the consumer goods sectors, the decline was 6.8 per cent and in investment goods 1.4 per cent.
The export prices of the industry in HUF increased by 1,1% compared to the previous month and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3,9%.
The price of our national currency fell by 1.7% against the euro and by 7.1% against the dollar in one month, compared with August 2007 when it strengthened by 7.5% against the euro and 15.9% against the dollar.
