Járóka: We must break the vicious circle of poverty and segregation
The European Summit on Equal Opportunities has opened in Paris today. It is being hosted by France, which is also the European Union's President-in-Office this year.
Lívia Járóka, MEP for the European People's Party (Fidesz), in her speech to the plenary, as one of the main speakers at this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education because it is one of the most serious violations that hit Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevailing foundation of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of MEPs in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Gypsies are left out of the labour market primarily because of their low level of education.
"Most young Roma have not completed secondary education and because of the poor quality of basic education, only a negligible part can obtain a university diploma".
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevailing foundation of other human rights as well.
Investing in the early education of Roma children can strengthen the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
The MEPs also called for the EU to take the necessary steps to ensure that the EU's citizens are given the right to vote and to stand as a candidate for the EU's presidency.
The earlier a Gypsy student starts school, the more likely he will be to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes he will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - said Lívia Járóka.
The European Parliament is also expected to take a decision on the future of the EU's education system, which will be implemented by the Commission in the coming months.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility guaranteed by democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens", Járóka said.
The objective of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, which has been organised annually since last year's Berlin meeting, under the banner of the 'European Year of Equal Opportunities', is to ensure a unique forum for promoting the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
