When energy is born from the waves, the great ones come down to the stage
It's an extinct deposit that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and is being discovered now by the world's big energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources that big companies like Chevron are looking at.
The possibility of harvesting energy from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, together with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was shelved, but now that environmental issues and the new oil boom are giving the sector a boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated that by 2007 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by devices that exploit the movement of ocean waves.
This would be twice as much as is produced by nuclear power plants today.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Giants to the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an implant in northern Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies are betting on marine energy, and among these companies are those who have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology", a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is considering cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It's a pretty important sign, considering that in Alaska the U.S. is still drilling for oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to drill for more.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are following the path of energy from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed, indicates an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in its infancy, because there is no doubt that marine energy has a great environmental impact.
For now, impacts like those in Portugal or Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, a technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas joined together.
The force of the waves, which moves the boas up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure turns a turbine, which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast via submarine cables.
Right now there are four such implants under development, pending federal approval only, apart from the energy, could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot, using underwater turbines in New York's East River.
The movement of water at high tide causes the turbine paddles to rotate, creating a rotary motion that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said he has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permits to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electrical Energy, is the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It's mostly tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others that are approaching the coast, have invested $7.5 million in 2008 and are planning to invest $35 million by 2009.
